    "narrative": "For LawDog today, we are leaning into high-upside matchups against mediocre arms to maximize our 5x5 categorical output. **Lawrence Butler** (74.61) represents our strongest play of the day; he benefits from an elite 5.60 xERA matchup against Fedde and a significant park factor boost, making him a primary source for power and potential run production. **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (70.83) remains a foundational anchor in the UTIL slot, thriving against a mid-tier Kremer, while **Luis Arraez** (63.69) is primed for a high-efficiency performance against Cavalli, where the park factors and favorable platoon splits elevate his base projection to a high-confidence start. **Masyn Winn** (62.13) also draws special attention; while the matchup against McCullers Jr. is standard, his elite sprint speed gives us the edge we covet in the scarcity-driven stolen base category, making him a locked-in MI start.\n\nOur most difficult bench decision involved **Drew Gilbert**, who finished with a 49.15, narrowly missing the cutoff behind our OF group. While **Drew Gilbert** projects reasonably well in the park-adjusted environment of a Cavalli start, he is relegated to the pine because his lower-order placement (8th) suppresses his run and RBI upside compared to higher-leverage hitters like **Jung Hoo Lee** or **Taylor Ward**. We are also exercising caution with **Cal Raleigh** (44.43). Despite his status as an everyday starter, he is currently dealing with a difficult matchup against Eovaldi, whose 3.17 xERA is the toughest on our board today; we are starting him for the power potential, but he represents our lowest-scoring active player and requires monitoring. Aside from the typical risk of an elite arm, we have no major weather concerns, though managers should watch for late-breaking lineup changes for **Jeremiah Jackson**, who is currently slotted into the #9 hole against the high-velocity threat of Williams.",
